        "body": "### Prerequisites\n\n- [x] I have written a descriptive issue title\n- [x] I have searched existing issues to ensure the bug has not already been reported\n\n\n### Mongoose version\n\n6.x.x\n\n### Node.js version\n\n14.x,\n\n### MongoDB server version\n\n5.x\n\n### Typescript version (if applicable)\n\nNot using TypeScript for this reproduction (JavaScript only)\n\n### Description\n\nWhen mongoose.set('autoCreate', true) is used, models registered on the default connection correctly auto-create their collections.\nHowever, models registered on a new connection created via mongoose.createConnection() do not inherit this global option.\n\nThis results in inconsistent behaviour between connections.\n\n### Steps to Reproduce\n\n```import mongoose from 'mongoose';\n\nmongoose.set('autoCreate', true);\n\nconst uri = 'mongodb://localhost:27017/test';\n\nconst User1 = mongoose.model('User1', new mongoose.Schema({ name: String }));\n\nconst conn = mongoose.createConnection(uri);\nconst User2 = conn.model('User2', new mongoose.Schema({ name: String }));\n\nawait mongoose.connection.asPromise();\nawait conn.asPromise();\n\nawait User1.init(); // ✓ collection created\nawait User2.init(); // ✗ collection NOT created\n```\nExpected: Both collections should be created.\nActual: Only the model on the default connection respects autoCreate.\n\n**Root Cause**\ncreateConnection() initialises its own connection.options without inheriting mongoose.options, so global settings like autoCreate never reach models created on additional connections.\n\n### Expected Behavior\n\n**Proposed Fix**\n\nMerge global and connection-level options inside the Connection constructor:\n\n```this.options = Object.assign({}, base.options, options);```\n\n\nI’ve already implemented and tested this locally.\nIf this behavior is confirmed as unintended, I’d be happy to open a PR with the fix and accompanying test.\n",
