        "body": "### Increasing access\n\nThis change would make contributing to p5.js easier and more approachable, especially for new contributors, educators, and creative coders who might not have prior experience with older build tools.\nGrunt has served p5.js well, but it can be slow and intimidating for beginners. Migrating to ESBuild, a faster and simpler tool, lowers that barrier — making it easier for more people (including those from historically underrepresented groups in art and tech) to get started with development, testing, and learning how p5.js works behind the scenes.\n\n### Most appropriate sub-area of p5.js?\n\n- [ ] Accessibility\n- [ ] Color\n- [ ] Core/Environment/Rendering\n- [ ] Data\n- [ ] DOM\n- [ ] Events\n- [ ] Image\n- [ ] IO\n- [ ] Math\n- [ ] Typography\n- [x] Utilities\n- [ ] WebGL\n- [x] Build process\n- [ ] Unit testing\n- [ ] Internationalization\n- [ ] Friendly errors\n- [ ] Other (specify if possible)\n\n### Feature enhancement details\n\nThe current p5.js build system uses Grunt for concatenation, minification, and task management.\nWhile functional, Grunt has become outdated — builds are slower, configurations are verbose, and maintenance is more complex than it needs to be.\n\nI’d like to migrate the build process to ESBuild, a modern JavaScript bundler that is:\n\nExtremely fast (written in Go, often 50–100× faster than Grunt).\nSimpler — a single Node.js script can replace multiple Grunt plugins.\nModern — supports ES modules, source maps, and tree-shaking by default.\nLow maintenance — fewer dependencies and faster CI/CD pipelines.",
